events.body:
~~Also now seeing:
xcrun: error: unable to find utility "c", not a developer tool or in PATH
when doing depends builds with macOS 10.13.5, Xcode 9.4.1 and CommandLine Tools 10.0.~~
This was caused by local depends changes...

I'm getting a lot of these when I use depends:

```
ld: warning: direct access in function 'QTreeWidget::qt_static_metacall(QObject*, QMetaObject::Call, int, void**)' from file '/Volumes/SSD/src/bitcoin/depends/x86_64-apple-darwin17.7.0/lib/libQt5Widgets.a(qtreewidget.o)' to global weak symbol 'QMetaTypeId<QItemSelection>::qt_metatype_id()::metatype_id' from file 'qt/libbitcoinqt.a(libbitcoinqt_a-moc_receivecoinsdialog.o)' means the weak symbol cannot be overridden at runtime. This was likely caused by different translation units being compiled with different visibility settings.
```

How do you get the command line tools version?

I am seeing this too (macOS 10.13.6, XCode 10.0 10A255).

I tried following [this](http://sd.jtimothyking.com/2018/07/26/stub-file-and-library-file-out-of-sync/) and it didn't work (why would it, after all installing the new command line tools just brought this about in the first place).

I'm wondering if one was to re-create these tbd files from the associated dylib file which it is a stub of, if the warnings go away (see https://github.com/Siguza/tbdump). Anyways I do not think it's anything that can be solved in the build system. I also wonder if this happens on a freshly installed mac (my guess is: probably not).

Seeing as the .tbd is out of sync with its own Framework, unless there's some voodoo going on behind the scenes, this looks like a bug in Apple's frameworks to me.

Do the resulting binaries behave as expected?
@theuni From what I've seen they do. If there's anything in particular you'd like tested let me know.

events.body:
I'm getting these errors now on macOS 10.14.1 even without using depends. It's pretty annoying (because useful warnings get snowed under).

Deleting and reinstalling Xcode tools doesn't help.

Apple [forum](https://forums.developer.apple.com/thread/97850) says:

> You have to link directly to the library and not rely on -isysroot or -frameworks in your makefile. you need to link like -L /path/to/lib libstuff.dylib
I'm no longer seeing these warnings.
